%%%%%%%%%%Question one
\begin{question}

\qpart

The equation of a straight line has the general form
	\[y = mx +c\]
	\hfill Where m is the gradient and c is the intercept

Given our two coordinates $(3,5)$ and $(5,4)$:
\begin{align*}
m &= \frac{y_{2} - y_{1}}{x_{2} - x_{1}}\\[8pt]
&= \frac{4 - 5}{5 - 3}\\[8pt]
&= \frac{-1}{2}
\end{align*}

Substituting this, and our coordinates: 
\begin{align*}
mx + c &= y\\[8pt]
\frac{-1}{2}(3) + c &= 5\\[8pt]
-1.5 +c &= 5\\[8pt]
c &= 6.5\\[8pt]
\shortintertext{Hence the equation of the line is;}
y &= \frac{-1}{2}x + 6.5
\end{align*}

\qpart

Using:
	\[ax^2 + bx + c = a(x + r)^2 + s\]

\begin{align*}
\shortintertext{Given:}
f(x) &= x^2 - 6x -4\\[8pt]
\shortintertext{By completing the square:}
&= (x - 3)^2 -9 -4\\[8pt]
&=  (x - 3)^2 - 13
\end{align*}

\qpart

\begin{align*}
\shortintertext{Solve;}
x^2 - 6x - 4 &= 0\\[8pt]
\shortintertext{Using the completed square form;}
(x - 3 )^2 - 13 &= 0\\[8pt]
(x - 3)^2 &= 13\\[8pt]
x - 3 &= \pm\sqrt{13}\\[8pt]
x &= 3 \pm\sqrt{13}
\end{align*}

\qpart

For the line \( y = \frac{-1}{2}x + 6.5 \).\\

The \( y-intercept \) is when \( x = 0 \) therefore \( y = 6.5 \).\\
The \( x-intercept \) is when \( y = 0 \) therefore \( x = 13 \).\\

For the curve \( y = x^2 + 6x -4 \);
The solutions are \( 3 \pm \sqrt{13} \).\\
The \( y-intercept \) is when \( x = 0 \) therefore \( y = -4 \).\\

The turning point;

\begin{align*}
y &= x^{2} - 6x -4\\[8pt]
\frac{dy}{dx} &= 2x -6\\[8pt]
2x - 6 &= 0\\[8pt]
2x &= 6\\[8pt]
x &= 3\\[8pt]
\stext{Substituting this back into the equation;}\\[8pt]
y &= 3^{2} -6(3) -4\\[8pt]
y &= -13\\
\end{align*}

Therefore \( (3,-13) \)

And the two curves meet at;
\begin{align*}
\frac{-1}{2}x + 6.5 &= x^{2} - 6x -4\\[8pt]
\frac{-1}{2}x &= x^{2} - 6x -\frac{21}{2}\\[8pt]
0 &= x^{2} - 5.5x - \frac{21}{2}\\[8pt]
&= 2x^{2} - 11x - 21\\[8pt]
&= (2x + 3)(x - 7)\\[8pt]
\stext{the x-coordinates are \( x = \frac{-3}{2} \text{ and } x = 7 \) }\\[8pt]
\stext{Substituting these back into our equation of the line;}\\[8pt]
y &= \frac{-1}{2}(\frac{-3}{2}) + 6.5\\[8pt]
&= \frac{29}{4}\\[8pt]
\stext{and}\\[8pt]
y &= \frac{-1}{2}(7) + 6.5\\[8pt]
&= 3\\ 
\stext{therefore the curves meet at \( (\frac{-3}{2},\frac{29}{4})  \text{ and }  (7,3) \).}\\
\end{align*}

\includegraphics[scale=0.7]{5.png}

\end{question}
\clearpage
%%%%%%%%%%Question two%%%%%%
\begin{question}

Solve:
	\[\frac{2x - 7}{3x + 1} \geq 0\]

The critical values the values which make either the denominator or the numerator $0$;\\
\begin{align*}
\shortintertext{So for $2x - 7$ when;} 
	x &= 3.5\\[8pt]
	2(3.5) -7 &= 0
\shortintertext{For $3x + 1$;}
	x &= \frac{-1}{3}\\[8pt]
	3\left(\frac{-1}{3} +1\right) &= 0
\end{align*}

We can use a table of signs:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
\hline
& $(-\infty,\frac{-1}{3})$ & $\frac{-1}{3}$ & $(\frac{-1}{3},3.5)$ & $3.5$ & $(3.5,\infty)$\\
\hline
$2x-7$ & $-$ & $-$ & $-$ & $0$ & $+$\\
$3x+1$ & $-$ & $0$ & $+$ & $+$ & $+$\\
\hline
$\frac{2x-7}{3x+1}$ & $+$ & $*$ & $-$ & $0$ & $+$\\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

As we want the values $\geq 0$ we would use the $+$ and $0$ values of the table of signs; 

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
\hline
& \cellcolor{red!25}$(-\infty,\frac{-1}{3})$ & $\frac{-1}{3}$ & $(\frac{-1}{3},3.5)$ & \cellcolor{red!25}$3.5$ & \cellcolor{red!25}$(3.5,\infty)$\\
\hline
$2x-7$ & \cellcolor{red!25}$-$ & $-$ & $-$ & \cellcolor{red!25}$0$ & \cellcolor{red!25}$+$\\
$3x+1$ & \cellcolor{red!25}$-$ & $0$ & $+$ & \cellcolor{red!25}$+$ & \cellcolor{red!25}$+$\\
\hline
$\frac{2x-7}{3x+1}$ & \cellcolor{red!25}$+$ & $*$ & $-$ & \cellcolor{red!25}$0$ & \cellcolor{red!25}$+$\\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Using this we get:
	\[x \in \left(-\infty,\frac{-1}{3}\right) \cup [3.5,\infty)\]

\end{question}
\clearpage
%%%%%%%%%%%Question three
\begin{question}

\qpart

We model the population size \( y \) over time \( t \) in months using the equation:
	\[y = Ae^{kt}\]	\hfill Where $A$ and $k$ are constants.
	
Given that after 2 months there were 30 rabbits and after 5 months there were 80 rabbits, we can set up the following pair of simultaneous equations:

\begin{align*}
30 &= Ae^{2k} \tag{1} \\
80 &= Ae^{5k} \tag{2}
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\stext{Dividing equation (2) by equation (1) gives:}\\[8pt]
\frac{80}{30} &= \frac{Ae^{5k}}{Ae^{2k}}\\[8pt]
\stext{Applying the index laws, this simplifies to:}\\[8pt]
\frac{80}{30} &= e^{5k-2k}\\[8pt]
\frac{8}{3} &= e^{3k}\\[8pt]
\stext{Taking the natural logarithm of both sides:}
\ln\left(\frac{8}{3}\right) &= 3k\\[8pt]
\stext{Solving for \( k \), we get:}
k &= \frac{1}{3} \ln\left(\frac{8}{3}\right)\\
\snote{as required.}
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\stext{Now, to find \( A \), using equation (1):}\\[8pt]
30 &= A e^{2k}\\[8pt]
A &= \frac{30}{e^{2k}}\\[8pt]
\stext{We substitute \( k = \frac{1}{3} \ln\left(\frac{8}{3}\right) \):}\\[8pt]
A &= \frac{30}{e^{2\frac{1}{3} \ln\left(\frac{8}{3}\right)}} \\[8pt]
&= \frac{30}{e^{\frac{2}{3} \ln\left(\frac{8}{3}\right)}}\\[8pt]
\stext{Using the exponent rule \( e^{a \ln(b)} = b^a \), we further simplify:}\\[8pt]
A &= \frac{30}{\left(\frac{8}{3}\right)^{\frac{2}{3}}}\\[8pt]
\stext{Calculating this, we find:}\\[8pt]
A &\approx 15.6
\snote{(to 1 d.p.)}
\end{align*}

\qpart

Using these values gives us:
\[
y = 15.6e^{t \left( \frac{1}{3}\ln\left(\frac{8}{3}\right)\right)}
\]

To find the time taken for the population to exceed \( 1000 \):

\begin{align*}
15.6e^{t \left( \frac{1}{3}\ln\left(\frac{8}{3}\right) \right)} &= 1000 \\[8pt]
\stext{Divide both sides by \( 15.6 \):}\\[8pt]
e^{t \left( \frac{1}{3}\ln\left(\frac{8}{3}\right) \right)} &= \frac{1000}{15.6}\\[8pt]
\stext{Taking the natural logarithms of both sides:}\\[8pt]
t \frac{1}{3} \ln\left(\frac{8}{3}\right) &= \ln\left(\frac{1000}{15.6}\right)\\[8pt]
\stext{Dividing both sides by \( \frac{1}{3} \ln\left(\frac{8}{3}\right) \):}\\[8pt]
t &= \frac{\ln\left(\frac{1000}{15.6}\right)}{\frac{1}{3} \ln\left(\frac{8}{3}\right)}\\[8pt]
t &\approx 12.72 \dots
\end{align*}

Therefore, using our model, it would take approximately \( 13 \) months for the population to exceed \( 1000 \).


\end{question}
